The Limit of Panic
Copenhagen—We often hear about how the world as we know it will come to an end, and the usual explanation is ecological collapse.
In fact, since the Club of Rome published the seminal work "The Limits to Growth" over forty years ago, its core ideas have been accompanying us.
But time is not forgiving.
"The Limits to Growth" published in 1972 warned humanity that a catastrophic collapse was imminent.
However, since then we have seen financial panics, but no real shortages or production collapses.
On the contrary, the resources created by human genius have more than adequately met human consumption.
But the core idea of "The Limits to Growth" still holds: we continue a trend of being preoccupied with misleading solutions to minor issues while neglecting the big problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, the optimism about technology faded, the Vietnam War became a disaster, society plunged into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book "Silent Spring" ignited public fear of pollution and also sparked the modern environmentalist movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 book "The Population Bomb" explained it all.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, people were filled with pessimism.
The intent of "The Limits to Growth" was to make people worry about resource depletion.
This is our fate, because too many people consume too much.
Even though our genius has bought us some time, we will ultimately destroy the Earth and ourselves through pollution.
The only hope is to stagnate economic growth itself, reduce consumption, recycle, and force people to have fewer children, achieving social stability at a level of poverty significantly higher than today.
This view still resonates today, despite being completely wrong.
For example, the authors of "The Limits to Growth" predicted that the world would run out of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc before 2013.
However, although commodity prices have recently rebounded, overall they have fallen to one-third of the levels from 150 years ago.
Technological innovation replaced mercury in batteries, dentistry materials, and thermometers, leading to an 98% decline in mercury consumption and a 90% drop in prices by the year 2000.
More broadly, since 1946, the supply of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc has exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical new extraction technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally expected to be exhausted by 1990 and 1992 respectively; today, their reserves are higher than the 1970 levels, despite a significant increase in our consumption.
In the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential natural gas reserves in the United States and cut prices in half.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14 times by the end of this century, with developing countries seeing an increase of 24 times.
"The Limits to Growth" was wrong because its authors overlooked the greatest resource: our own ingenuity.
Population growth began to slow down since the 1960s.
Food supply has not collapsed (1.5 billion hectares of arable land are being used, and there are an additional 2.7 billion hectares in reserve).
The rate of malnutrition has been reduced by more than half, dropping from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution has not posed a problem for us.
The Roman Club imagined a pastoral past where there was no air pollution from suspended particles and everyone was happy as farmers, while in the future, heating chimneys would make us unable to breathe. Reality is entirely the opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, yet nearly 3 million people—equivalent to one in every 500 people—died from air pollution each year, most of which was indoor air pollution.
Now, the proportion has dropped to one death per 2,000 people.
Although the number of deaths from pollution is still higher than that from malaria, the mortality rate is declining rather than rising.
Despite this, the ideas promoted by "The Limits to Growth" continue to shape the thinking of the public and elites.
Take recycling, for example; it is usually just a gesture that makes people feel better, costing a great deal to the environment with little effect.
For example, paper is usually sourced from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
The procedures related to paper recycling and government subsidies result in low-quality paper, protecting resources that are not actually threatened.
Similarly, concerns about overpopulation led to self-destructive policies, such as China's family planning policy and India's forced sterilization.
In addition, although pesticides and other pollutants were once believed to kill half of humanity, effective pesticide regulation has resulted in only 20 deaths per year in the United States, while pesticide use has created more affordable and abundant food supplies.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture — the movement spurred by pesticide panic — would add an extra $100 billion in costs to the United States each year.
Agricultural productivity would decrease by 16 percent, and to maintain current output, an additional 65 million hectares of farmland — half the size of modern-day California — would be needed.
Price increases will lead to a decline in fruit and vegetable consumption, causing serious negative health impacts (including an increase of tens of thousands of cancer-related deaths annually).
Being fixated on bleak scenarios prevents us from focusing on real global threats.
Poverty is one of the greatest killers, and easily curable diseases still cause the death of 15 million people each year — equivalent to a quarter of the total number of deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people escape poverty, most can afford the cost of preventing infectious diseases.
Over the past three decades, China has lifted 680 million people out of poverty, leading the world in reducing the number of people living in poverty by nearly a billion.
This has led to widespread improvements in health, lifespan, and quality of life.
The forty-year history since the release of "The Limits to Growth" shows that we need more, not less, growth.
The expansion of trade is estimated to bring more than 100 trillion dollars in benefits annually by the end of this century, far surpassing the meager "comfort" policies born from spreading fear.
But this requires abandoning the anti-growth mindset and using our boundless potential to create a brighter future.
